The maxMatching function in Java returns an integer. Let's translate that. In Java:

int maxMatching(int v, int p) {
    int a = 0;
    int o = 0;
    for (int w : g[v]) {
        if (w == p) continue;
        int r = maxMatching(w, v);
        a += r / 2;
        o += r % 2;
    }
    return 2 * a + Math.min(1, o) + 1;
} In Fortran, this is a recursive function. But Fortran can handle recursion if the function is declared as recursive. So, the function would look like:

recursive integer function max_matching(v, p) result(res)
    integer, intent(in) :: v, p
    integer :: a, o, r, w, i
    a = 0
    o = 0 do i = 1, size(g(v)%nodes)
        w = g(v)%nodes(i)
        if (w == p) cycle
        r = max_matching(w, v) a = a + r / 2
        o = o + mod(r, 2)
    end do
    res = 2*a + min(1, o) + 1
end function

Wait, but the adjacency list for v is stored in g(v)%nodes. So for each w in g(v)%nodes, we process them, skipping if w is p.
